1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Rb1 {This is a very aggressive move from White. The idea is to bring the Rook
immediately on the half-open b-file and make the pressure on b7 pawn. In this
variation in order to get the initiative White often sacrifices one, sometimes
even two pawns (a2 and c3 pawns).} O-O 9. Be2 cxd4 10. cxd4 Qa5+ {Black's idea
here is to take the advantage of the fact that White's King is still in the
center and with this move he wants to take the pawn on a2, or if White wants
to exchange the Queens than Black will have pawns' majority on the queenside.}
11. Bd2 {Main move. Alternative is 11.Qd2 while after 11...Qd2 12.Bd2 position
is equal.} (11. Qd2 {White doesn't allow Black to take the pawn on a2, but
with this move somehow do not play with the idea of sacrificing the pawn in
order to get the initiative. After this move position is completely equal.}
Qxd2+ 12. Bxd2) 11... Qxa2 12. O-O Bg4 {This is the main and in my view the
best move in the position. Black wants to take the pawn on d4 for the moment;
White doesn't have enough time to take the pawn on b7.} (12... b6 {In this
position this is the main alternative to Bg4. Idea is to develop the
light-squared Bishop to b7 and protect the b pawn by moving it to b6. Next,
Black wants to put the pressure on e4 pawn and after this playing Nc6 and push
on the d4 square. The drawback is that after this Queen will be wrongly placed
on the queenside and potentially can be in a great danger. In this line White
can easily make the draw by repetition, attacking exposed Black's Queen.} 13.
Qc1 Bb7 14. Bc4 Qa4 15. Bb5 Qa2 16. Re1 (16. Bc4 Qa4 17. Bb5 $11 {This is the
draw.}) 16... Rc8 17. Qd1 Qc2 18. Qe2 Nc6 19. Bd3 Qa2 20. Bc4 $14 {White has a
small advantage because Black's Queen is in the danger and also White have a
very nice initiative for the sacrificed pawn.}) 13. Bg5 {With this move White
attacks the pawn on e7, but the main reason for playing it is in the fact that
he needs to defend the d4 pawn.} (13. Be3 $5 {Alternative to Bg5. White makes
extra protection for his d4 pawn but now this Bishop does not attack the e7
pawn.} Nc6 14. d5 Na5 15. Bg5 Qa3 16. Bd2 $13 {Position is very unclear. Black
has his extra pawn, but his pieces: the Knight and the Queen are very exposed
and White has a full compensation.}) 13... h6 14. Bh4 (14. Bxe7 $6 {This is
not the good move. White takes on e7 but stays without his e4 pawn and his
center collapses. Black has after this an equal play and White does not have
any initiative.} Re8 15. Rxb7 Nc6 16. Bc5 Rxe4 $11) 14... a5 {This is the main
Black's idea. This passed pawn give him very active play.} 15. Rxb7 g5 16. Bg3
a4 (16... Nc6 $5 {This is a nice alternative to 16...a4. Here Black first
wants to develop his last piece - Knight on b8 and then move the "a" pawn.} 17.
d5 Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Nd4 19. Rxe7 a4 $13 {Now White has an extra pawn but Black
gets the initiative. Black stays with the perfect pieces: his Queen, a nice
Bishop on g7 and a great Knight on d4. All together with the Rook on a8 all
Black pieces are supporting advancing of the a pawn.}) 17. h4 Nc6 18. hxg5 hxg5
19. d5 (19. Nxg5 $4 Bxe2 $19) 19... Bxf3 20. Bxf3 Nd4 {That is a very good
position for Black. All his pieces play very well and they control all vital
squares. Position is about equal but Black has the initiative.} 21. d6 e5 22.
d7 Qe6 {Now Black will take one pawn back, either d7 or e4. Next few moves was
perfectly played by both sides.} 23. Bg4 Qc6 24. Rb1 Qxe4 25. Re1 Qd5 26. Bf5
Rad8 27. Be4 {White gets his Bishop on the dominant square in the center and
now he wants to attack the Black's King.} Qe6 28. Qh5 f5 {Black can not play
without this move. Now his King is a little bit exposed.} 29. Bd3 $6 (29. Rb6
$5 Qf7 30. Qxf7+ Kxf7 31. Bd5+ Ke7 32. Rg6 f4 33. Rxg7+ Kd6 34. Bc4 fxg3 35.
fxg3 Rxd7 $11 {with an equal endgame and most likely the game will be finished
as a draw.}) 29... Rxd7 30. Rbc1 Qh6 {White makes the wrong decision with 29.
Bd3. Now he needs to exchange the Queen and the game is clearly better for
Black because of the extra pawn.} 31. Qxh6 Bxh6 32. Bxe5 Bg7 33. Rc7 {Last
mistake. This move looks very nice but is clearly a mistake.} (33. Bxd4 Rxd4
34. Rc3 $15 {And White has a chance to hold this position.}) 33... Rxc7 {Now
Black is winning.} 34. Bxc7 Bf6 35. Rb1 a3 $17 36. Kf1 Kg7 37. Bc4 Rh8 38. Kg1
a2 39. Bxa2 Ne2+ 40. Kf1 Nc3 41. g4 Nxb1 0-1

