This White Knight originally plays a defensive role and defends d4 pawn and
here he plays very active because the Black Knight is on the wrong square.} (
14. Bxe7 {After this move and exchange of the "e" pawn position will be equal.
That's why White brings into the play his Knight from f3.} Re8 15. Bc5 Rxe4)
14... f6 15. Nd3 $6 {Now White misses the best move. After 15. Nd3 Black will
have enough time to consolidate his position.} (15. Ra1 $5 {This was the right
move. White needs to play very actively and bring all pieces into the play.}
Qe6 16. Bg4 f5 17. exf5 gxf5 18. Bf3 $16 {Now is clear that White is much
better. All White pieces are better developed than those of Black and Black is
without a single good move. Black has an extra pawn but White is much better.})
15... Qf7 16. d5 $6 (16. Nc5 $5 {White brings the Knight on the dominant c5
square and his center stays very nice.}) 16... f5 $5 {Great move. Now Black
opens the center and takes over the initiative.} 17. Nc5 fxe4 18. d6 {This was
White's idea. But now Black has 18...Rd8 and after this eventually he will
exchange booth central pawns. Position will be close to equal but it will be
much easier to play with Black's pieces here.} Rd8 19. Nxe4 Bf5 20. Bd3 Bxe4 $6
(20... exd6 $5 {This was much better. Now Black is better.} 21. Nxd6 Rxd6 $1
22. Bxd6 Rd8 $1 23. Bxf5 gxf5 $17 {White can not escape with his Bishop and
Black will have two piece for the Rook and a better position.}) 21. Bxe4 exd6
$11 22. f4 $6 {Bad move. Now after 22...d5 Black will be much better.} (22. Bf3
$11) 22... d5 23. Bc2 Nc4 24. Rb3 $6 {This is the Final mistake. White lost
